                    of 3.25 years after the diagnosis (range 0.08–9.0 years)    
                    6,011 participants died, of which 3,619 (60.2%) was due to  
                    breast cancer. After adjustment for age, tumor              
                    characteristics, and treatment selection, both              
                    post-diagnostic and pre-diagnostic statin use were          
                    associated with lowered risk of breast cancer death (HR     
                    0.46, 95% CI 0.38–0.55 and HR 0.54, 95% CI 0.44–0.67,       
                    respectively). The risk decrease by post-diagnostic statin  
                    use was likely affected by healthy adherer bias; that is,   
                    the greater likelihood of dying cancer patients to          
